<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="68" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="68">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="68">
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, JM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 169" title="A revision of the genera Mycetoporus Mannerheim and Ischnosoma Stephens (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Tachyporinae) of North and Central America." url="10.4039/entm123156fv" volume="119" year="1991">Campbell (1991)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species from various of wetland habitats as well as forests. Adults were taken from flood debris along rivers, margins of beaver ponds, beaver lodges, muskrat nests, mallard (
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Anatidae" genus="Anas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anas platyrhynchos" order="Anseriformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="68" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="platyrhynchos">Anas platyrhynchos</taxonomicName>
L.) nests, moss near seepage areas, leaf litter along margins of marshes, streams, and bogs, and various kinds of grass and leaf litter from conifer and deciduous forests (
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, JM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 169" title="A revision of the genera Mycetoporus Mannerheim and Ischnosoma Stephens (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Tachyporinae) of North and Central America." url="10.4039/entm123156fv" volume="119" year="1991">Campbell 1991</bibRefCitation>
). Recent studies in Alberta (mid-boreal ecoregion) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Buddle, CM" journalOrPublisher="Biological Conservation" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="346 - 357" title="Arthropod responses to harvesting and wildfire: implications for emulation of natural disturbance in forest management." url="10.1016/j.biocon.2005.10.002" volume="128" year="2006">Buddle et al. (2006)</bibRefCitation>
indicated that this species was associated with old (&gt;70-year-old) fire-origin, mixed wood forest stands. Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pohl, GR" journalOrPublisher="Biological Conservation" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="294 - 307" title="Rove beetles and ground beetles (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Carabidae) as indicators of harvest and regeneration practices in western Canadian foothills forests." url="10.1016/j.biocon.2007.02.011" volume="137" year="2007">Pohl et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
reported that this species was also associated with regenerating mixed wood stands in the western foothills of Alberta. The specimens from New Brunswick were collected in moldy conifer duff and fleshy gilled mushrooms in a small balsam fir (
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Abies" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Abies balsamea" order="Pinales" pageId="13" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="balsamea">Abies balsamea</taxonomicName>
(L.) Mill.) (regenerating) stand adjacent to a hardwood forest. 
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell, JM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada" pageId="21" pageNumber="76" pagination="1 - 169" title="A revision of the genera Mycetoporus Mannerheim and Ischnosoma Stephens (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Tachyporinae) of North and Central America." url="10.4039/entm123156fv" volume="119" year="1991">Campbell (1991)</bibRefCitation>
reported most specimens of this species were taken in June to September. The specimens from New Brunswick were collected during May and September.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
